### Meaning 

# Total elevation gain: significant for men, null for women. At the course level (n=6, so treat cautiously), gain correlates strongly with men's times (r = 0.83, p = 0.043) but not women's at all (r = 0.09, p = 0.87). The race-level regression (the trustworthy one, n≈144 per sex) confirms this cleanly: men lose 0.81 seconds per metre of elevation gain (p < 0.001, highly significant), women show essentially nothing (0.16 s/m, p = 0.57).
#Net elevation: the opposite pattern — stronger for men, weaker for women, but same direction both times. Men lose 0.82 seconds of benefit per metre of net downhill (p = 0.0015, significant); women show a similar-sized effect (0.71 s/m) but it doesn't reach significance (p = 0.124), likely just underpowered rather than genuinely absent given the effect size is comparable to men's.
#The honest, interesting takeaway: hilliness — both total climbing and net drop — appears to matter substantially for elite men's times, but the evidence for women is much weaker or absent depending on which elevation measure you use. That's worth flagging rather than glossing over, and it's a genuinely publishable-sounding contrast for the write-up:
##"Course elevation profile showed a strong relationship with elite men's average times: each additional metre of total elevation gain cost approximately 0.81 seconds (p < 0.001), and each metre of net downhill saved a comparable 0.82 seconds (p = 0.002). Neither relationship reached significance for women, though the net elevation effect was directionally similar and of comparable magnitude (0.71 s/m, p = 0.124), suggesting this may reflect the smaller women's sample rather than a true absence of the effect. Total elevation gain showed no meaningful relationship with women's times in either the course-level or race-level analysis."

